<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn Rejects Russian Claims of Housing Delay </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2502142294 Berlin DIE WELT in German 25 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU2502142294 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Bonn Rejects Russian Accusations"] </F>
  [Text] Bonn -- The Federal Government has rejected the 
accusations by Colonel General Burlakov, commander in chief of 
the Russian forces in Germany, concerning alleged delays in the 
housing construction program for returning soldiers as 
unjustified. In a statement to the Bundestag Budget Committee, 
Mr. Goehner parliamentary state secretary in the FRG Economics 
Minister, stressed that the originally agreed goal of completing 
36,000 apartments by the end of 1994 is not in danger as far as 
one can say at the moment. 
  Goehner said that Burlakov's repeated accusations are due to 
his duty to care for his soldiers. According to the Russian 
Defense Ministry, about 220,000 apartments for soldiers are 
currently missing, and Germany's contribution is just 
alleviating the problem. 
  According to Goehner, some interim building deadlines have 
not been observed. The delays are three months at the most. 
The biggest delays happened in 1992. According to the state 
secretary, 15,000 apartments are finished. In total, the 
Federal Government provides 8.35 billion marks, with which at 
least 45,000 apartments in 40 building sights, including all 
technical and social infrastructure are being built. In 
addition, two housing construction combines and about 20 
factories for building and equipment materials are part of the 
program. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

