<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rexrodt Endorses U.S. Trade Pressure on Japan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2502004594 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0307 GMT 22 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2502004594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 21 Feb (NOTIMEX) -- The German 
Government supports the U.S. position of getting Japan to open 
its market "not only in words but with actions," German Economy 
Minister Gunter Rexrodt said here today. The official 
emphasized, however, that Germany's support for Washington would 
be limited if the United States simply wishes to establish 
export or market quotas, because such measures could damage all 
international trade. 
  Last week, the United States announced it will retaliate 
against Japan because the Far Eastern nation has not allowed 
several U.S.-made products to enter its market. 
  The German minister, who has been on an official visit here 
since last Thursday [17 February], asserted that placing limits 
on exports will only lead to bilateralism, which runs against 
multinational agreements. He explained that such a decision 
"would violate GATT and would conflict with the interests of the 
world's large exporting nations." 
  Rexrodt said his country's investments in Mexico will 
increase if Mexico signs an agreement for reciprocal promotion 
and protection of investments. In 1993, 31 percent of Mexico's 
exports to Europe went to Germany and, in turn, Germany became 
Mexico's foremost commercial partner in the region. 
  After meeting with Mexican Foreign Secretary Manuel Tello 
Macias, Rexrodt explained that Germany has given Mexico priority 
status in its relations with Latin America. An example of this, 
he said, is the "Technogerma Mexico 1994" industrial fair, which 
was inaugurated by Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari 
on Monday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

