<F P=100> PORTUGAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Relations With Israel Reviewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302101594 Lisbon Radio Renascenca in Portuguese to Europe 
0900 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2302101594 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon Radio Renascenca </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] There are clear signs that relations between Lisbon 
and Tel Aviv are improving. Miguel Coimbra reports: 
  [Coimbra] Portugal has had diplomatic relations with Israel 
since 1977, but it only opened an embassy in Tel Aviv two and a 
half years ago. Since then there have been successive high 
level visits and meetings between leaders of both countries. 
These meetings have resulted in excellent cooperation relations 
and in the development of a variety of activities -- 
entrepreneurial, scientific, and commercial. Israel has become 
in the last few years, OECD countries aside, Portugal's second 
trading partner, after Angola. The good relations are also 
demonstrated by the two direct weekly flights between Portugal 
and Israel and by an accord to abolish entry visas for citizens 
of the two countries. In addition to strengthening bilateral 
understanding, the two governments are at the moment working on 
the consolidation of cooperation on a trilateral level, 
including the PALOP's [Lusophone African countries], and on an 
international level with a focus on the Middle East peace 
process and on a new economic accord between Israel and the 
European Union. 

</TEXT>

