<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Proposals for Agricultural Support `Unacceptable' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2402150094 Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 23 Feb 94 
p 5 </F>

<F P=103> PM2402150094 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["EvS" report: "Finland Dissatisfied With New EU </F>
Classification"] 
  [Text] Brussels -- Finland showed its great 
dissatisfaction with the new EU [European Union] regional 
support classification and will continue to argue that large 
areas of Finland need Objective 1 support instead of the 
Objective 6 support which was proposed by the EU yesterday. 
  The EU's proposal in the field of agriculture was also 
completely unacceptable to Finland: 
  "Only 5 percent of agricultural production would be 
covered," 
Under Secretary of State Veli Sundback said. 
  Foreign Minister Heikki Haavisto said that the criteria for 
receiving agricultural support are so numerous and wide-ranging 
that Finland cannot accept the proposal, but will return with a 
counterbid at the weekend after careful study. 
  In some areas, however, Haavisto was able to note forward 
movement. A special protocol protecting the Lapps' way of life 
was accepted by the EU. Foreigners will be granted the right to 
buy leisure homes in Finland. The issue of herring fishing in 
the Baltic Sea has also been resolved. This means that EU 
citizens will be able to fish herring for use as mink and fox 
food, with a promise of a review and an investigation of herring 
stocks after three years. However, the issue of regulations 
covering travelers remains to be resolved. 

</TEXT>

