<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman on Gligorov's `Diplomatic Impropriety' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2402153194 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2402153194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos today 
described as diplomatic impropriety the move by [The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM, President Kiro] Gligorov 
to make his letter to the Greek prime minister public before it 
was actually delivered to Papandreou. The government spokesman 
reiterated that the Greek Government received the letter with 
some reservations, since it bore the name Macedonia. It merely 
received the letter so that it might learn the content and study 
it. 
  Venizelos said the European Union's [EU] Dutch Commissioner 
Hans van den Broek established Skopje's intransigence, so he 
might have realized, even belatedly, why Greece adopted these 
measures. Asked if Van den Broek asked the Greek Government to 
lift the measures, Venizelos said he had not, because Greece 
insists on its positions. Only when there is practical proof of 
Skopje's goodwill could our country lift the measures and 
reconsider its stance on Skopje's accession to the CSCE. Only 
then, the government spokesman stressed, will we resume the 
dialogue under the auspices of the United Nations and Cyrus 
Vance. The subject of the dialogue will be Greece-Skopje's 
economic cooperation and the name, on which Greece's position is 
well known. 
  Venizelos said he hoped the Dutch commissioner's initiative 
would continue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

