<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Sees `Russia Problem' for West </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2502152094 Paris AFP in English 1503 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2502152094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Rome, Feb 25 (AFP) -- Italian Defense Minister 
Fabio Fabbri said Friday [25 February] Western nations were 
again facing a Russia problem, but urged them to deal with it 
with dialogue and firmness. 
  "The void left by the Warsaw Pact cannot last long. Either 
the West fills it or Russian hegemony will return," Fabbri told 
journalists here. 
  "The West is again facing a Russia problem," he said, adding 
that this "delicate issue must be treated by combining dialogue 
and firmness." 
  Russia was politically and economically weak but its 
conventional and nuclear weapons also made it strong, he said, 
adding that its weaknesses and internal contrasts could explain 
why it was "asking for a new Yalta and claiming a freedom of 
action in what it defines as its intangible sphere of influence." 
  He was referring to the Yalta accords, reached between 
Stalin, Roosevelt and Churchill three months before the end of 
World War II, by which the Soviet Union gained hegemony over 
East Europe. 
  Fabbri said statements by Italy's opposition communists that 
NATO had outlived itself and should be disbanded were "not in 
the interest of Italy, Europe or the West." 
  "Never more than today has the Atlantic Alliance been a 
pillar of security for the West and the international order." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

